abstract = {This research employs the Modified differential evolution (DE) algorithm and incorporates Random Forest Regression for forecasting renewable energy. The primary emphasis is on optimizing power generation within a smart building microgrid, where economic and ecological factors play a crucial role. To address this complexity, a nonlinear multi-objective optimization equation is formulated, encompassing a variety of constraints to reduce operating costs and environmental impact. The study introduces an artificial intelligence technique based on DE to tackle both multi-objective and single-objective optimization challenges within the microgrid, showcasing its versatility across different scenarios. The algorithm accommodates scenarios with unrestricted power exchange and considers constraints on power exchange with the upstream network, providing a comprehensive approach to multi-objective optimization. Additionally, the research explores the impact of renewable energy resources (RERs) on costs by maximizing their utilization, conducting a comparative analysis with Particle Swarm Optimization (PSO) using real-time data. The study validates the effectiveness of this innovative energy management approach through a range of scenarios. Shifting focus to the realm of renewable energy microgrids, the integration of digital twins heralds a transformative era for sustainable energy systems. This article delves into the diverse applications of digital twins, which are virtual replicas of physical microgrid infrastructures, in the modeling and optimization of renewable energy components. The digital twin encompasses renewable sources such as solar panels and wind turbines, simulating their behavior under varying environmental conditions.}
